St. Columba could hardly have been ignorant of the discrepancy, yet he evinced no desire to alter the existing practice, and such was the respect for his memory in after times, that the bare fact of his observance of the old rule operated, during more thau a century, as the great obstacle to the adoption of the Roman Easter in the monastery of Hy and its depen- dencies; on the principle stated by Colman: “Numquid reverentissimum patrem nostrum Columbam, et successores ejus viros Deo dilec- tos, qui eodem modo pascha fecerunt, divinis paginis contraria sapuisse, vel egisse, creden- dum est ?'’ In fact this discordia was a pro— tracted struggle between the chair of St. Peter and old associations, though the advantage of argument lay with the former.
